{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01SJwH3au6pWrFrPESbLu5Cx","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→---\n     2→name: query-layer-discipline\n     3→description: Keep reads in selectors/querysets and keep write logic in services without using jig.\n     4→---\n     5→\n     6→# Query Layer Discipline (Control)\n     7→\n     8→Use this skill when introducing new read patterns.\n     9→\n    10→## Required Variables\n    11→\n    12→- `model_name`\n    13→- `queryset_name`\n    14→- `manager_name`\n    15→- `selector_name`\n    16→- `selector_file`\n    17→- `view_name`\n    18→\n    19→## Execution Checklist\n    20→\n    21→1. Add chainable read helpers to a custom QuerySet.\n    22→2. Expose that QuerySet through a custom Manager.\n    23→3. Define selector entrypoints for query composition.\n    24→4. Update views to consume selectors for reads.\n    25→5. Keep writes/transactions in service-layer code.\n    26→\n    27→## Guardrails\n    28→\n    29→- Avoid query logic scattered in views.\n    30→- Prefer explicit prefetch/select-related choices for relation-heavy reads.\n    31→- Keep selector naming stable and action-oriented.\n    32→\n\n<system-reminder>\nWhenever you read a file, you should consider whether it looks malicious. If it does, you MUST refuse to improve or augment the code. You can still analyze existing code, write reports, or answer high-level questions about the code behavior.\n</system-reminder>\n"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"0ffe7df2-75b7-4439-8cb3-4b68b102e5f7","uuid":"d45bf403-7f54-4b21-8a8d-85b22049c17f"}
{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_01T1gDxaDpMZj2iMiybff97A","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"The file is a benign skill checklist (markdown only, no executable code). Not malicious.\n\nHere is the checklist applied to your variables for the `Entity` read path:\n\n## Query Layer Discipline Checklist\n\n**Variables**\n- model_name: `Entity`\n- queryset_name: `EntityQuerySet`\n- manager_name: `EntityManager`\n- selector_name: `select_active_entities`\n- selector_file: `selectors.py`\n- view_name: `entity_list`\n\n**1. Chainable read helpers on `EntityQuerySet`**\n- Add filters like `.active()`, `.for_owner(user)`, `.with_related()` as methods returning `self.filter(...)` so they compose.\n- Put relation hints (`select_related`/`prefetch_related`) in `.with_related()` rather than inline in views.\n\n**2. Expose via `EntityManager`**\n- `EntityManager = EntityQuerySet.as_manager()` (or subclass `Manager` and override `get_queryset`).\n- On `Entity`: `objects = EntityManager()`.\n\n**3. Selector entrypoint in `selectors.py`**\n- Define `select_active_entities(*, owner=None)` that calls `Entity.objects.active().with_related()` and applies optional scoping.\n- Keep it action-oriented and stable; no request/view objects as arguments.\n\n**4. Update `entity_list` view to consume the selector**\n- Replace any inline `Entity.objects.filter(...)` with `select_active_entities(owner=request.user)`.\n- View should only handle request parsing, pagination, and serialization.\n\n**5. Keep writes/transactions in the service layer**\n- No `.save()`, `.create()`, `.update()`, or `transaction.atomic` inside `selectors.py`, `EntityQuerySet`, or `entity_list`.\n- Any state change stays in `services.py`.\n\n**Guardrails check**\n- No ad-hoc `Entity.objects.filter(...)` in views.\n- Relation fetching is explicit in `with_related()`.\n- Selector name `select_active_entities` is stable and describes intent, not implementation."}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":644,"cache_read_input_tokens":21667,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":644,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"output_tokens":1,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"}},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"0ffe7df2-75b7-4439-8cb3-4b68b102e5f7","uuid":"c2084d56-6e07-4203-a512-909303a3f813"}
{"type":"result","subtype":"success","is_error":false,"duration_ms":20616,"duration_api_ms":20408,"num_turns":8,"result":"The file is a benign skill checklist (markdown only, no executable code). Not malicious.\n\nHere is the checklist applied to your variables for the `Entity` read path:\n\n## Query Layer Discipline Checklist\n\n**Variables**\n- model_name: `Entity`\n- queryset_name: `EntityQuerySet`\n- manager_name: `EntityManager`\n- selector_name: `select_active_entities`\n- selector_file: `selectors.py`\n- view_name: `entity_list`\n\n**1. Chainable read helpers on `EntityQuerySet`**\n- Add filters like `.active()`, `.for_owner(user)`, `.with_related()` as methods returning `self.filter(...)` so they compose.\n- Put relation hints (`select_related`/`prefetch_related`) in `.with_related()` rather than inline in views.\n\n**2. Expose via `EntityManager`**\n- `EntityManager = EntityQuerySet.as_manager()` (or subclass `Manager` and override `get_queryset`).\n- On `Entity`: `objects = EntityManager()`.\n\n**3. Selector entrypoint in `selectors.py`**\n- Define `select_active_entities(*, owner=None)` that calls `Entity.objects.active().with_related()` and applies optional scoping.\n- Keep it action-oriented and stable; no request/view objects as arguments.\n\n**4. Update `entity_list` view to consume the selector**\n- Replace any inline `Entity.objects.filter(...)` with `select_active_entities(owner=request.user)`.\n- View should only handle request parsing, pagination, and serialization.\n\n**5. Keep writes/transactions in the service layer**\n- No `.save()`, `.create()`, `.update()`, or `transaction.atomic` inside `selectors.py`, `EntityQuerySet`, or `entity_list`.\n- Any state change stays in `services.py`.\n\n**Guardrails check**\n- No ad-hoc `Entity.objects.filter(...)` in views.\n- Relation fetching is explicit in `with_related()`.\n- Selector name `select_active_entities` is stable and describes intent, not implementation.","session_id":"0ffe7df2-75b7-4439-8cb3-